        "source_anchor": "https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference/unsafety.html#unsafety",
        "source_fetched_at": "2026-02-20T19:26:06+00:00",
        "statement_id": "doc::unsafety.md::section:0001::statement:001",
        "statement_text": "r[safety.intro] Unsafe operations are those that can potentially violate the memory-safety guarantees of Rust's static semantics. r[safety.unsafe-ops] The following language level features cannot be used in the safe subset of Rust: r[safety.unsafe-deref] - Dereferencing a [raw pointer]. r[safety.unsafe-static] - Reading or writing a [mutable] or unsafe [external] static variable. r[safety.unsafe-union-access] - Accessing a field of a [`union`], other than to assign to it. r[safety.unsafe-call] - Calling an unsafe function. r[safety.unsafe-target-feature-call] - Calling a safe function marked with a [`target_feature`][attributes.codegen.target_feature] from a function that does not have a `target_feature` attribute enabling the same features (see [attributes.codegen.target_feature.safety-restrictions]). r[safety.unsafe-impl] - Implementing an [unsafe trait]. r[safety.unsafe-extern] - Declaring an [`extern`] block[^extern-2024]. r[safety.unsafe-attribute] - Applying an [unsafe attribute] to an item.",
